.SH git\-adr\-init(1) \(en Initialize ADR tracking in a repository
.SS SYNOPSIS
\f[CR]git adr init\f[R] OPTIONS
.SS DESCRIPTION
Initialize Architecture Decision Record tracking in the current git
repository.
This command sets up the git notes namespace for storing ADRs and
configures remote fetch/push refspecs for ADR synchronization.
.SS OPTIONS
.TP
\f[CR]\-\-force\f[R], \f[CR]\-f\f[R]
Reinitialize even if git\-adr is already initialized.
Useful for reconfiguring after adding new remotes.
.TP
\f[CR]\-\-namespace\f[R] TEXT
Custom git notes namespace (default: \f[CR]refs/notes/adr\f[R]).
.TP
\f[CR]\-\-template\f[R] [madr|nygard|y\-statement]
Default template format for new ADRs (default: madr).
.TP
\f[CR]\-h\f[R], \f[CR]\-\-help\f[R]
Show help message and exit.
.SS WHAT GETS CONFIGURED
Running \f[CR]git adr init\f[R] performs the following:
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]Notes namespace\f[R]: Creates the ADR notes namespace in git
config.
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]Remote refspecs\f[R]: For each configured remote, adds fetch and
push refspecs for the ADR notes:
.RS 4
.IP
.EX
remote.origin.fetch = +refs/notes/adr:refs/notes/adr
remote.origin.push = refs/notes/adr
.EE
.RE
.IP "3." 3
\f[B]Notes rewrite behavior\f[R]: Configures git to preserve ADR notes
during rebase and amend operations:
.RS 4
.IP
.EX
notes.rewriteRef = refs/notes/adr
notes.rewrite.rebase = true
notes.rewrite.amend = true
.EE
.RE
.IP "4." 3
\f[B]Initialization marker\f[R]: Sets \f[CR]adr.initialized = true\f[R]
to indicate the repository is configured for git\-adr.
.SS EXAMPLES
Basic initialization:
.IP
.EX
$ git adr init
.EE
.PP
Initialize with a specific template:
.IP
.EX
$ git adr init \-\-template nygard
.EE
.PP
Reinitialize after adding a new remote:
.IP
.EX
$ git remote add upstream https://github.com/org/repo.git
$ git adr init \-\-force
.EE
.SS NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
Initialization is idempotent; running it multiple times is safe.
.IP \(bu 2
Use \f[CR]\-\-force\f[R] to update remote configurations after adding
new remotes.
.IP \(bu 2
The ADR namespace is separate from regular git notes, avoiding
conflicts.
